1 Retirement Administrator's key findings for higher education employees of the Southeastern
2 Conference schools; and
3 WHEREAS, long-term employees who transition from the ORP to the TRSL defined
4 benefit plan later in their careers face an inability to apply prior years of service toward
5 vesting requirements; and
6 WHEREAS, differences exist in the treatment of accrued leave, as defined benefit
7 plan members may convert unused leave into service credit, while ORP participants receive
8 limited or no comparable benefit; and
9 WHEREAS, ORP participants may be subject to state income taxation on retirement
10 distributions in circumstances where defined benefit plan retirees are exempt; and
11 WHEREAS, prior task force efforts have not fully addressed the differences affecting
12 long-term ORP participants or evaluated targeted remedies for this population; and
13 WHEREAS, the House of Representatives requires comprehensive, objective, and
14 updated information in order to evaluate potential reforms and ensure equitable retirement
15 outcomes for all public education employees.
16 THEREFORE, BE IT RESOLVED that the House of Representatives of the
17 Legislature does hereby establish a task force to study the Optional Retirement Plan within
18 the Teachers' Retirement System of Louisiana, with a specific focus on differences affecting
19 long-term participants and options for achieving greater parity with the defined benefit plan.
20 BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED that the task force shall examine, including but not
21 limited to, the following:
22 (1) The feasibility and potential design of granting pension service credit to long-
23 term ORP participants, including those who have transitioned to the defined benefit plan and
24 those who have not, based on actuarial years of service, in exchange for the transfer of ORP
25 account balances, with or without requiring the purchase of such credit, including
26 consideration of graduated or tenure-based approaches, and taking into account historical
27 employer contribution levels to the ORP in evaluating actuarial equity.
28 (2) The development of hybrid or partial retirement benefit models for both current
29 long-term ORP participants and recent transfers, combining elements of defined contribution
30 and defined benefit plans to improve retirement security.
