1 (3) Alternatives to the current five-year vesting requirement for employees who
2 transition from the ORP to the defined benefit plan later in their careers, including
3 recognition of prior service or accrued leave.
4 (4) Policies to provide equitable treatment of accrued leave for ORP participants
5 and recent pension transfers, including actuarial conversion of leave into ORP retirement
6 accounts, direct payment of accrued leave at retirement, or application toward vesting
7 requirements.
8 (5) The feasibility of allowing ORP participants who transfer to alternative providers
9 to receive the same state tax exemptions on their retirement income as TRSL defined benefit
10 retirees.
11 (6) A review of employer contribution rates to the ORP, including historical
12 changes, the extent to which such rates have been reduced or redirected, the impact of
13 contributions toward the pension system's unfunded accrued liability, and the resulting
14 effects on ORP participants' ability to accumulate sufficient retirement savings, including
15 lost opportunities to supplement and grow their ORP accounts.
16 (7) The impact of the absence of Social Security coverage for ORP participants and
17 recent pension transfers, and options to address resulting retirement income gaps.
18 (8) Identification of long-term ORP participants and recent transfers, including those
19 with twenty or more years of service, and evaluation of targeted remedies to address
20 differences affecting this population.
21 (9) A review and reassessment of prior task force findings and recommendations
22 related to the ORP and identification of any gaps.
23 (10) The impact of irrevocable ORP election decisions on employees with
24 intermittent or non-continuous service, including those who return to public education after
25 extended absences and are subsequently ineligible for participation in the defined benefit
26 plan, as well as those who transition to the defined benefit plan later in their careers but
27 encounter difficulties in meeting vesting requirements, and the feasibility of providing
28 alternative enrollment pathways or targeted remedies for such individuals.
29 BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED that the task force shall be composed of members
30 appointed as follows:
